Scott: I guess I'll go and skip to the end and listen to this question.

611
00:38:40,680 --> 00:38:41,560
Scott: That was a pretty good question.

612
00:38:41,800 --> 00:38:42,260
Scott: That has been cheesed.

613
00:38:43,185 --> 00:38:44,080
Scott: A cheesed question.

614
00:38:44,240 --> 00:38:51,800
Rym: Listener, I did not catch your name and because of COVID protocols, the enforcers of course shooed almost everyone out of the room so we couldn't interact too much.

615
00:38:51,880 --> 00:38:54,569
Rym: So if you're listening to this, email us.

616
00:38:54,990 --> 00:38:57,860
Rym: I will happily answer your question in more detail via email.

617
00:38:59,963 --> 00:39:02,079
Scott: Okay, we can finally get to the main bit.

618
00:39:02,281 --> 00:39:03,520
Rym: Finally get to the main bit.

619
00:39:03,900 --> 00:39:16,239
Rym: This is something that I spent a lot of time thinking about in middle school and high school because you kids don't realize what it was like to try to play games.

620
00:39:17,621 --> 00:39:23,900
Rym: In this case, we're pretty much only talking about PC games, like multiplayer PC games for the most part.

621
00:39:24,421 --> 00:39:40,600
Rym: If you wanted to play Quake or Doom or any one of those games like Command & Conquer against someone else, you had to know like the phone number of a special service to dial, the actual direct IP address of a specific server that someone was running.

622
00:39:41,061 --> 00:39:41,912
Rym: How were they running it?

623
00:39:42,256 --> 00:39:42,540
Rym: Magic.

624
00:39:43,022 --> 00:39:46,360
Rym: I didn't know how to run a server until like late high school.

625
00:39:48,161 --> 00:39:53,440
Scott: Yeah, I mean, you know, the way that I played multiplayer PC games was of course local, right?

626
00:39:54,080 --> 00:39:57,375
Scott: Whether you're sitting at the same computer with two input devices or a LAN.

627
00:39:59,221 --> 00:40:04,620
Scott: All the computers are just plugged into the same hub and you connect that way using IPX or something.

628
00:40:06,263 --> 00:40:07,488
Scott: And then you've got the dial up.

629
00:40:07,609 --> 00:40:10,260
Scott: One person opens up their modem, the other person dials the modem.

630
00:40:10,400 --> 00:40:13,414
Scott: You call it, you're effectively just making a phone call and then playing.

631
00:40:13,434 --> 00:40:14,640
Scott: I've done that method.

632
00:40:16,185 --> 00:40:19,718
Scott: But yeah, because, you know, we don't have IPv6 really, right?

633
00:40:20,320 --> 00:40:25,394
Scott: It's like you could, you know, go to like open up Half-Life back in the 90s or early 2000s and be like click new game.

634
00:40:28,121 --> 00:40:31,760
Scott: And then that would sort of create a server and run the game locally.

635
00:40:31,881 --> 00:40:36,239
Scott: And then someone else could try to find your game either in the game list or typing in your IP.

636
00:40:37,100 --> 00:40:42,820
Rym: Good luck actually making that work the way people's houses and internet actually worked at the time.

637
00:40:43,503 --> 00:40:52,900
Scott: Yeah, especially so your computer, even if you could get the networking part to work, your computer had to run the server and the game for you, the client for you at the same time.

638
00:40:52,960 --> 00:40:55,779
Scott: So you needed a very powerful computer for this to be a good experience.

639
00:40:55,880 --> 00:40:56,620
Scott: Oh my god, remember in RIT?

640
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:00,280
Scott: Especially if there were more than just a few players, right?

641
00:41:01,421 --> 00:41:11,100
Rym: Remember in RIT when we were playing Ricochet locally with IPX and our neighbors like bullshit firewall detected it and they called campus safety on us claiming we were hacking them?

642
00:41:12,061 --> 00:41:12,281
Scott: Yeah.

643
00:41:12,542 --> 00:41:20,220
Scott: Anyway, so what happened is you basically had to just run a game server.

644
00:41:20,340 --> 00:41:27,440
Scott: You would get a computer that was dedicated to doing nothing else, but running the game server, the computer would have a publicly accessible IP address.

645
00:41:28,103 --> 00:41:30,599
Scott: And now everybody who wanted to play could connect to the server.

646
00:41:31,043 --> 00:41:33,060
Scott: Their local computer would only have to run the client.

647
00:41:33,522 --> 00:41:43,160
Scott: And as long as your network connection to the server was solid and low latency enough, 100 or less usually, hopefully even less than that, maybe less than 50 if you're really good.

648
00:41:43,680 --> 00:41:45,439
Scott: A single digit if you're in college, right?

649
00:41:46,041 --> 00:41:48,618
Rym: A single digit for me in high school for reasons I'll get into.

650
00:41:50,060 --> 00:41:57,538
Scott: But anyway, then multiplayer PC gaming became a good, decent experience in the early 2000s, late 90s.

651
00:41:58,941 --> 00:42:00,260
Rym: Now it was a fascinating time.

652
00:42:00,440 --> 00:42:07,560
Rym: I think we'll start by talking about what it was like to be a player and then we can talk about what it was like and the challenges of actually running a server.

653
00:42:08,023 --> 00:42:10,460
Rym: And then what sort of killed this and what the current state of things are.

654
00:42:10,620 --> 00:42:15,920
Rym: Because those are the three main interesting topics here that don't overlap other GeekNights episodes we've already done.

655
00:42:16,621 --> 00:42:22,260
Rym: As a player, you got to understand, this was already a rarefied experience.

656
00:42:22,720 --> 00:42:36,900
Rym: The tiniest percentage of people who even had access to a computer that could play a game like Quake had the ability, knowledge, and community to play it online with significant numbers of other people.

657
00:42:37,182 --> 00:42:40,280
Rym: That was already very rare for most people.

658
00:42:41,402 --> 00:42:46,000
Scott: It might be common if you go to, say, a nerdy college, everyone's playing Counter-Strike in every room.

659
00:42:46,480 --> 00:42:48,940
Scott: But worldwide, almost nobody.

660
00:42:50,040 --> 00:42:55,660
Rym: And even most college kids, when we were in high school, not a lot of colleges even had this stuff set up.

661
00:42:56,609 --> 00:42:57,399
Scott: Only the nerdy ones.

662
00:42:57,861 --> 00:43:01,820
Rym: RIT was notable in that it had a, for real, campus network that worked.

663
00:43:02,561 --> 00:43:06,100
Scott: And even if the college wasn't nerdy, there might be a nerdy section of the college.

664
00:43:06,260 --> 00:43:08,793
Scott: Like just the people in the CS department, but no one else.

665
00:43:08,974 --> 00:43:10,200
Scott: The whole rest of the college wasn't in it.

666
00:43:10,520 --> 00:43:13,540
Rym: So in high school, like skipping modems, because that's a little dicey.

667
00:43:13,640 --> 00:43:15,560
Rym: If I wanted to play Quake online on a server.

668
00:43:16,180 --> 00:43:22,420
Rym: One, I had to know a community of people online who lived pretty close to me.

669
00:43:22,480 --> 00:43:25,300
Rym: Like they had to live in Southeast Michigan or it wouldn't work.

670
00:43:25,540 --> 00:43:26,939
Rym: Internet was a lot slower back then.

671
00:43:27,080 --> 00:43:30,240
Rym: Like so much slower and so much higher latency.

672
00:43:30,701 --> 00:43:32,960
Rym: Whatever you think it was like, you were wrong.

673
00:43:33,061 --> 00:43:34,359
Rym: Unless you were as old as us or older.

674
00:43:34,960 --> 00:43:42,760
Rym: So I had to just somehow know like a bunch of people who lived in Southeast Michigan who all played Quake.

675
00:43:43,403 --> 00:43:44,700
Rym: All had similar sensibilities.

676
00:43:45,440 --> 00:43:55,140
Rym: And knew someone in our collective circles who had the arcane knowledge to run a public Quake server with a real IP address.

677
00:43:55,742 --> 00:44:00,800
Rym: So it was some rich white kid usually running a server on like dedicated hardware.

678
00:44:01,423 --> 00:44:05,600
Rym: And the local community of people playing one specific game.

679
00:44:05,780 --> 00:44:11,920
Rym: And only that game would find each other on BBS's and web-based forums and bulletin boards.

680
00:44:13,241 --> 00:44:18,020
Rym: I spent a lot of time in IRC just watching for is anyone playing Quake?

681
00:44:18,361 --> 00:44:25,840
Rym: Because if anyone I know is playing Quake, they would post in IRC the IP address or often just the name of the server they were on.

682
00:44:26,340 --> 00:44:28,720
Rym: Because some of the servers were kind of exclusive.

683
00:44:29,261 --> 00:44:35,160
Rym: Like Bunnies was a place I would play where it was only chill cool people and people tried to win.

684
00:44:35,942 --> 00:44:41,021
Rym: And it had like a 20 millisecond ping even in 1997.

685
00:44:41,021 --> 00:44:46,420
Scott: And the thing is, you know, not all of the servers, right?

686
00:44:46,440 --> 00:44:49,580
Scott: It's not like today where you can just get a server list, right?

687
00:44:49,861 --> 00:44:52,215
Scott: It's like, ah, here are all the Quake servers, right?

688
00:44:52,255 --> 00:44:53,000
Scott: Let me choose one.

689
00:44:53,241 --> 00:44:55,900
Scott: It's like back in those days, there wasn't a server list.

690
00:44:56,001 --> 00:44:57,458
Scott: It was type in the IP here.

691
00:44:58,301 --> 00:45:01,840
Scott: There might have been some other software that was separate that you could use.

692
00:45:04,046 --> 00:45:08,880
Scott: It might list servers, but people had to add their servers to those lists on purpose, right?

693
00:45:09,801 --> 00:45:17,200
Scott: If someone wasn't advertising to the world that they have a server at an IP address, finding it was going to be very, very difficult.

694
00:45:17,300 --> 00:45:23,440
Rym: But even worse, the more well known the IP address was of a server, the more dipshits were there.

695
00:45:23,580 --> 00:45:25,920
Rym: And the more popular it was, you try to log in, it's full.

696
00:45:26,660 --> 00:45:32,020
Rym: I spent a lot of time, literally, I would just sit there at my computer, like looking at the internet.

697
00:45:32,361 --> 00:45:38,160
Rym: Well, I had Quake open constantly trying to connect to the IP address of a good server because it was full.

698
00:45:38,200 --> 00:45:41,212
Scott: Because as soon as someone quits, there's a spot open.

699
00:45:41,232 --> 00:45:43,280
Scott: It's first come, first served digitally.

700
00:45:43,640 --> 00:45:44,959
Scott: If you can get that spot, you're in.

701
00:45:45,801 --> 00:45:48,834
Rym: And generally, if the server was full, that's a hopping server.

702
00:45:48,874 --> 00:45:50,260
Rym: You definitely want to be there.

703
00:45:50,701 --> 00:45:52,240
Rym: If a server lets you in right away, it's usually empty.

704
00:45:52,360 --> 00:45:59,940
Scott: Sure, you could join a server that's got two people playing and hope that maybe there's a lot of people who are currently refreshing and trying to join the full server.

705
00:46:00,321 --> 00:46:04,379
Scott: And if they see the server with two people go to three and four, they might go to that one.

706
00:46:05,121 --> 00:46:06,900
Scott: And this only works, though, when there's a server listing.

707
00:46:08,486 --> 00:46:10,364
Scott: But the more public servers... Sometimes it doesn't happen.

708
00:46:10,384 --> 00:46:13,560
Scott: Sometimes you go to the server with two people and no one comes and it's like, god damn it.

709
00:46:13,900 --> 00:46:19,400
Rym: So there were a bunch of Quake 1 and Quake 2 servers running various mods and some of them were vanilla in my area.

710
00:46:19,800 --> 00:46:27,080
Rym: But most of them, there were people there, but they were bad people, they were griefers and trolls and cheaters and all this crap.

711
00:46:27,680 --> 00:46:36,640
Rym: So separately, there was a list of servers that I knew about and the people I knew knew about from private IRC that weren't listed on all those websites.

712
00:46:37,042 --> 00:46:39,719
Rym: And those were the cool places where chill people would hang out.

713
00:46:41,661 --> 00:46:46,620
Scott: But it was harder for those ones to have enough people to be playing.

714
00:46:47,100 --> 00:46:50,599
Scott: It was more rare that you would go there and actually get a good game going on.

715
00:46:51,020 --> 00:46:53,400
Scott: Because it's not open to the public with lots of players coming all the time.

716
00:46:53,460 --> 00:46:53,962
Scott: Except Bunnies.

717
00:46:54,022 --> 00:46:58,880
Rym: Bunnies was pretty much full 24/7 because that was the best server in Southeast Michigan.

718
00:46:59,601 --> 00:47:02,952
Rym: And you had to... Bunny had to talk to you to vet.

719
00:47:02,992 --> 00:47:05,159
Rym: you were a chill person before they'd even tell you the IP.

720
00:47:06,081 --> 00:47:10,840
Rym: And I was password protected and that was where I spent a lot of time playing Quake games back in the day.

721
00:47:11,500 --> 00:47:18,194
Rym: But you were 100% at the mercy of whoever out there ran the server.

722
00:47:18,535 --> 00:47:21,140
Rym: They were the dictator god as far as you were concerned.

723
00:47:22,280 --> 00:47:24,700
Scott: Yep, and the person running the server can do all sorts of nonsense.

724
00:47:24,900 --> 00:47:29,340
Scott: They can kick you, they can ban you, at least ban your IP based on what system it was.

725
00:47:29,420 --> 00:47:31,631
Scott: When Steam came around, they could ban your Steam ID.

726
00:47:31,832 --> 00:47:33,360
Scott: You need to get a whole new Steam account.

727
00:47:34,501 --> 00:47:36,049
Scott: They could change the rules on the server.

728
00:47:36,150 --> 00:47:37,215
Scott: They could change the gravity.

729
00:47:37,315 --> 00:47:38,160
Scott: They could change the map.

730
00:47:38,660 --> 00:47:40,369
Scott: They could change fucking anything.

731
00:47:40,489 --> 00:47:42,600
Scott: Anything that was a Quake variable, right?

732
00:47:43,120 --> 00:47:46,380
Rym: I had three different versions of Weapons Factory, a mod for Quake 2 installed.

733
00:47:46,500 --> 00:47:51,800
Rym: Because all the different servers I connected to were all running different versions of the mod that were mutually incompatible.

734
00:47:52,620 --> 00:47:53,344
Scott: Yeah, they could cheat.

735
00:47:55,354 --> 00:47:56,500
Scott: They could do whatever the hell they wanted.

736
00:47:56,600 --> 00:47:57,510
Scott: They ran the server.

737
00:47:57,732 --> 00:47:58,460
Scott: They were in charge.

738
00:47:58,620 --> 00:47:59,950
Scott: The people who made the game have no say.

739
00:47:59,990 --> 00:48:01,360
Scott: The people playing the game have no say.

740
00:48:01,681 --> 00:48:07,260
Scott: The person running the server is like a GM in old school D&D where they just do whatever they want.

741
00:48:07,440 --> 00:48:09,048
Scott: And that was, in some ways, good.

742
00:48:09,952 --> 00:48:11,720
Scott: And in some ways, not good.

743
00:48:11,940 --> 00:48:15,399
Rym: Yep, like you talk about today, like, "Oh, without matchmaking, gaming

744
00:48:15,419 --> 00:48:15,520
Rym: sucks.".

745
00:48:16,442 --> 00:48:19,100
Rym: This is so far beyond without matchmaking.

746
00:48:19,781 --> 00:48:20,379
Scott: Yeah, right?

747
00:48:22,022 --> 00:48:22,907
Rym: And I had a lot of fun.

748
00:48:22,927 --> 00:48:25,180
Rym: And it was a really interesting time.

749
00:48:25,581 --> 00:48:27,653
Rym: But those days also sucked.

750
00:48:27,894 --> 00:48:36,099
Rym: They were a giant pain in the... I had a notepad file that was the list of, like, the specific servers I could play each game I cared about on.

751
00:48:36,921 --> 00:48:37,333
Rym: And that was it.

752
00:48:38,401 --> 00:48:38,602
Scott: Yep.

753
00:48:39,707 --> 00:48:42,940
Scott: So, as time went on, right, things progressed a bit, right?

754
00:48:43,161 --> 00:48:45,699
Scott: The "run your own server" got a little bit easier.

755
00:48:48,203 --> 00:48:50,759
Scott: Some normal people could do it or just pay someone else to do it.

756
00:48:51,280 --> 00:48:57,020
Rym: Freshman year of RIT, I ran a Counter-Strike server, a really crappy one, from my dorm room.

757
00:48:57,401 --> 00:49:00,618
Rym: And then Scott and I ran a much better one from our colony apartment.

758
00:49:01,020 --> 00:49:03,980
Scott: When I bought a new computer, the old computer ran the IcyWorld server.

759
00:49:04,260 --> 00:49:05,233
Scott: Yep, we ran an FYI.

760
00:49:05,940 --> 00:49:11,400
Scott: It wasn't a strong enough computer to run, like, Dust 2 or whatever, but IcyWorld is a tiny map, so it worked.

761
00:49:11,680 --> 00:49:11,740
Rym: Yep.

762
00:49:11,760 --> 00:49:14,695
Rym: We limited it to, what, like eight or ten players, I think.

763
00:49:14,876 --> 00:49:15,720
Rym: Otherwise it would lay out.

764
00:49:15,880 --> 00:49:17,480
Scott: Yeah, IcyWorld doesn't need that many players, right?

765
00:49:17,522 --> 00:49:17,798
Scott: Exactly.

766
00:49:18,802 --> 00:49:19,679
Scott: Per team, per team.

767
00:49:20,222 --> 00:49:23,940
Rym: I spent a lot of time playing on our dumpy little IcyWorld server at RIT.

768
00:49:24,240 --> 00:49:24,657
Scott: Yeah, me too.

769
00:49:24,921 --> 00:49:27,499
Rym: What I was very happy about is, it was always bumping.

770
00:49:28,041 --> 00:49:29,932
Rym: There were always people there, even if we weren't using it.

771
00:49:30,033 --> 00:49:31,119
Rym: I was very happy about that.

772
00:49:32,461 --> 00:49:35,520
Scott: Anyway, but yeah, running your own server got easier.

773
00:49:35,740 --> 00:49:40,580
Scott: There was the server listings that were run by the game developers, right, so it's easy to find games.

774
00:49:41,700 --> 00:49:45,360
Scott: You know, the anti-cheat technology came into play.

775
00:49:45,440 --> 00:49:49,320
Scott: There was already, like, existing anti-cheat, like Punkbuster, if anyone remembers that.

776
00:49:49,901 --> 00:49:54,640
Rym: Oh my god, I was not cool with Punkbuster until people were cheating so much.

777
00:49:55,023 --> 00:49:56,940
Rym: That I was willing to accept that malware.

778
00:49:57,741 --> 00:50:04,739
Scott: Yeah, then Valve came out with that VAC, right, which was much better, but not perfect anti-cheat, right?

779
00:50:06,203 --> 00:50:08,580
Scott: But yeah, you know, it was okay times, right?

780
00:50:08,680 --> 00:50:14,740
Scott: It was, they eliminated some of the problems of the old day, but you still had the fundamental same situation, right?

781
00:50:14,760 --> 00:50:17,720
Scott: Where a server is run by a person, that person is in charge.

782
00:50:19,261 --> 00:50:26,900
Scott: Every, you know, there aren't really, some of the games, their company might run a few servers of their own, just to create, like, a baseline.

783
00:50:27,422 --> 00:50:30,440
Scott: But people rarely played on those very much, right?

784
00:50:31,141 --> 00:50:36,780
Rym: And the cool part about that era, all those eras, was in the early days, they were just dictators.

785
00:50:36,940 --> 00:50:49,220
Rym: But that brief period where the ease of running a server expanded, we saw a lot of servers where people set up really fun and clever stuff.

786
00:50:49,480 --> 00:50:56,400
Rym: That sort of threw gasoline on the existing mod scene, and people were doing really interesting things.

787
00:50:56,720 --> 00:51:04,580
Rym: Some servers would have completely different rulesets, like, people were experimenting, whole communities would, like, form around weird servers.

788
00:51:05,182 --> 00:51:09,340
Rym: It was, honestly, a really fun time to be alive in terms of gaming, because you gotta wait for the-.

789
00:51:09,340 --> 00:51:12,958
Scott: Yeah, not all of those mods and customizations were, like, good as games.

790
00:51:13,300 --> 00:51:15,780
Rym: Oh, most of them were absolute dogshit, don't get us wrong.

791
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:22,740
Scott: Right, but it was still, like, a flourishing period of creativity and excitement and all sorts of, you know, there were lots of options.

792
00:51:23,681 --> 00:51:28,120
Scott: And you'd be surprised, like, what random Half-Life mod you could turn on and actually find players, right?

793
00:51:28,140 --> 00:51:29,567
Scott: It's like, Natural Selection.

794
00:51:29,567 --> 00:51:31,235
Scott: 1 was a Half-Life 1 mod.

795
00:51:31,476 --> 00:51:32,180
Scott: That's what it was.

796
00:51:32,320 --> 00:51:40,020
Scott: It wasn't a new game, you know, it's like, it was a Half-Life 1 mod, and if it wasn't for the ability to run your own server, it's like, it wouldn't have been possible.

797
00:51:41,142 --> 00:51:41,639
Scott: It never happened.

798
00:51:42,600 --> 00:51:52,780
Rym: So, it went from an era of a very small number of nerds with money and arcane knowledge could run these, to almost any nerd who cared could run this, like, it was pretty easy.

799
00:51:53,401 --> 00:51:56,850
Rym: But then, the server world, like, kind of went away.

800
00:51:56,890 --> 00:52:00,920
Rym: Like, in the modern era, very few people run their own servers.

801
00:52:01,080 --> 00:52:10,060
Rym: They're almost entirely reliant on the company that released the game will let people spawn games, but not necessarily dedicated servers.

802
00:52:10,241 --> 00:52:12,487
Rym: A lot of these companies will let you customize.

803
00:52:13,269 --> 00:52:16,940
Rym: Some games let you customize to extreme extents, like Overwatch.

804
00:52:17,402 --> 00:52:22,139
Rym: If you spawn a custom game, you can put some ridiculous mods in there.

805
00:52:23,040 --> 00:52:26,460
Scott: Right, but you can't make up your own mod, you can just choose from the mods that they're providing.

806
00:52:26,660 --> 00:52:27,999
Scott: It could be an extensive list.

807
00:52:28,460 --> 00:52:32,760
Rym: But you can also tune every parameter, you can import objects, there's a lot of customization.

808
00:52:32,821 --> 00:52:33,911
Scott: You can't write code, though.

809
00:52:33,931 --> 00:52:34,759
Scott: There's a line.

810
00:52:35,923 --> 00:52:39,320
Rym: You can get close to writing code with some of the modding capabilities.

811
00:52:39,320 --> 00:52:40,979
Scott: You couldn't make something like Natural Selection 1 Overwatch.

812
00:52:41,040 --> 00:52:41,546
Scott: You could not.

813
00:52:42,213 --> 00:52:42,779
Scott: Absolutely not.

814
00:52:42,860 --> 00:52:43,448
Scott: You could make another game.

815
00:52:43,489 --> 00:52:44,240
Scott: that's not Overwatch.

816
00:52:44,481 --> 00:52:47,940
Rym: Yeah, but if we just focus on the server aspect of it...

817
00:52:47,980 --> 00:52:49,658
Scott: You couldn't add some character that didn't exist.

818
00:52:51,241 --> 00:52:58,280
Rym: I don't think the fact that companies went this way is what killed people running their own dedicated servers.

819
00:52:58,460 --> 00:53:07,680
Rym: What killed it is the fact that the fatal flaw of all dedicated servers was that without matchmaking, you had to do manual matchmaking.

820
00:53:07,880 --> 00:53:17,280
Rym: Unless you played on servers where the people who played were all roughly your same skill level, gaming sucked.

821
00:53:17,680 --> 00:53:21,080
Rym: You were either better than everyone else or you died instantly every game no matter what.

822
00:53:21,860 --> 00:53:22,407
Rym: And that was it.

823
00:53:22,508 --> 00:53:23,500
Rym: There was zero middle ground.

824
00:53:23,780 --> 00:53:31,420
Scott: Because a lot of these games were skill-based, high skill cap games, if there were other games... That's also a consequence of the game itself.

825
00:53:31,620 --> 00:53:36,360
Scott: If you had been playing with a server of some other game that wasn't a high skill game, that wouldn't have happened.

826
00:53:36,661 --> 00:53:40,659
Scott: But you were playing Counter-Strike or Quake, so that was definitely what was going on.

827
00:53:41,061 --> 00:53:47,920
Rym: But most games that had dedicated server technology were competitive first person shooter ortho games.

828
00:53:48,140 --> 00:53:48,424
Scott: Of course.

829
00:53:48,993 --> 00:53:49,318
Scott: Of course.

830
00:53:49,600 --> 00:53:50,518
Rym: Because most other games...

831
00:53:50,620 --> 00:53:55,940
Scott: Who's going to go through the effort to do all that for, I don't know, for Candyland?

832
00:53:56,440 --> 00:54:01,500
Rym: And other games like Civilization and stuff like that really didn't have multiplayer capabilities.

833
00:54:02,280 --> 00:54:03,239
Scott: They did play by mail.

834
00:54:03,604 --> 00:54:03,900
Scott: Exactly.

835
00:54:03,961 --> 00:54:05,071
Scott: You couldn't even run a server.

836
00:54:06,320 --> 00:54:19,560
Rym: FPSs really were the emergence of that concept for most people of run a dedicated server, curate a community around it, and that is the place you play this game with your friends and your extended community.

837
00:54:20,241 --> 00:54:22,039
Rym: Nowadays, you do that via friends lists.

838
00:54:23,160 --> 00:54:26,760
Scott: So companies started running the servers themselves, and this had some pluses and minuses.

839
00:54:27,020 --> 00:54:27,522
Scott: We already talked about.

840
00:54:27,622 --> 00:54:31,800
Scott: one minus is the lack of the flourishing creativity of the mods and all that.

841
00:54:32,300 --> 00:54:32,858
Scott: But here's the plus.

842
00:54:33,021 --> 00:54:34,190
Rym: Quake 1 today, we want to play.

843
00:54:35,960 --> 00:54:38,840
Rym: I right click on all my friends' names in Quake.

844
00:54:38,940 --> 00:54:39,298
Scott: And it works.

845
00:54:39,600 --> 00:54:40,299
Rym: It just works.

846
00:54:40,640 --> 00:54:42,480
Rym: A server appears, my friends are in it.

847
00:54:42,480 --> 00:54:42,820
Scott: It works great.

848
00:54:43,080 --> 00:54:43,878
Rym: Nobody else is in it.

849
00:54:44,920 --> 00:54:45,675
Rym: Everyone has the same version.

850
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:47,336
Scott: No one has to go and update their...

851
00:54:47,766 --> 00:54:47,936
Rym: Yup.

852
00:54:48,442 --> 00:54:48,920
Rym: I make it public.

853
00:54:49,180 --> 00:54:52,297
Scott: No one gets a message like, "Oh, the server's got a newer version than you do, or an older

854
00:54:52,337 --> 00:54:52,679
Scott: version.".

855
00:54:52,880 --> 00:54:56,220
Rym: Random people do just join and play with us, and it's totally fun.

856
00:55:00,085 --> 00:55:02,940
Scott: Some of those games, you still can get your own maps in there, right?

857
00:55:03,201 --> 00:55:03,719
Scott: To an extent.

858
00:55:04,040 --> 00:55:04,110
Scott: Yup.

859
00:55:04,860 --> 00:55:05,355
Scott: Things like that.

860
00:55:06,602 --> 00:55:08,979
Scott: But the other players have to have the maps for it to work.

861
00:55:10,020 --> 00:55:23,860
Rym: But I guess it's a nuanced space, because it is true that we have lost some of the power and control and modability of servers and the unique aspects of running dedicated servers that you control in these games.

862
00:55:24,502 --> 00:55:29,778
Rym: But I think almost all of the pros of the modern era outweigh the cons, because...

863
00:55:30,464 --> 00:55:31,320
Scott: Yeah, they do outweigh.

864
00:55:31,500 --> 00:55:32,400
Rym: I can't stress this enough.

865
00:55:32,440 --> 00:55:42,280
Rym: Without matchmaking, orthogames online that are highly skill-based are absolutely unplayable now that so many more people play games.

866
00:55:43,260 --> 00:55:43,335
Scott: Yup.

867
00:55:44,401 --> 00:55:49,000
Scott: So some other positives, right, is that cheating has decreased.

868
00:55:49,380 --> 00:55:51,740
Scott: It's still out there, but it's decreased significantly.

869
00:55:51,740 --> 00:55:57,220
Rym: You had to find a server where the social contract was, "Nobody cheats," and the mod would actually ban people who cheated.

870
00:55:57,820 --> 00:55:59,740
Rym: That isn't a problem anymore.

871
00:56:00,021 --> 00:56:01,000
Rym: Nobody cheats at Overwatch.

872
00:56:01,100 --> 00:56:04,280
Rym: If someone cheats at Overwatch, they are banned by the company pretty quickly.

873
00:56:05,100 --> 00:56:09,920
Scott: You also don't have to worry too much about the server admin being some jerk, right?

874
00:56:10,241 --> 00:56:14,960
Scott: It's like the servers are all adminned by the company, which has the terms of service, right?

875
00:56:15,340 --> 00:56:23,493
Scott: It's like if you go to some old Quake server that's run out of someone's house, people there might be going, you know, "Racial slur, racial slur, racial slur,".

876
00:56:23,954 --> 00:56:25,740
Scott: and what are you gonna do about it?

877
00:56:25,860 --> 00:56:27,480
Scott: Report it to who, right?

878
00:56:27,560 --> 00:56:30,240
Scott: It's like the admin who's the one saying racial slur?

879
00:56:30,500 --> 00:56:31,800
Scott: The person who owns that computer?

880
00:56:32,160 --> 00:56:33,299
Scott: It's like, no, right?

881
00:56:33,380 --> 00:56:44,940
Scott: But if companies are running them as evil as corporate capitalist entities are, they can actually protect the player base with their terms of service and things of that nature.

882
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:56,820
Scott: And you'll get, you know, it's obviously they haven't completely solved the problem because plenty of people have shitty experiences on their servers all the time, but they can do something about it as opposed to nothing.

883
00:56:58,841 --> 00:57:02,920
Scott: So it's better, you know, even if it's still poopy.

884
00:57:04,180 --> 00:57:11,420
Rym: And I think maybe they're like, while there's more we could say, we've gone on over an hour, I'm hungry and I have to play Blades in the Dark like in an hour.

885
00:57:11,420 --> 00:57:18,054
Scott: Well, I think the one thing that really needs to be said is the major downside of the not being able to run your own server.

886
00:57:18,254 --> 00:57:20,920
Scott: is the game preservation aspect, right?

887
00:57:21,120 --> 00:57:38,159
Scott: All of these multiplayer game experiences, I think this really started with the MMOs and the MUDs, right, is that if the companies running these servers turn their shit off and they don't open source their code or whatever, then you can never experience these games again.

888
00:57:38,340 --> 00:57:38,660
Scott: Nobody.

889
00:57:38,740 --> 00:57:41,087
Scott: It's like they're just lost to time permanently.

890
00:57:41,107 --> 00:57:42,130
Scott: They're gone.

891
00:57:42,492 --> 00:57:43,475
Scott: There might be screenshots.

892
00:57:44,317 --> 00:57:45,260
Scott: There might be videos.

893
00:57:45,760 --> 00:57:51,250
Scott: There might be some, you know, there might be someone hacks together, like tries to reverse engineer the server or something.

894
00:57:51,310 --> 00:57:57,540
Scott: But unless that original server is running, it's a thing that humans can no longer experience.

895
00:57:57,640 --> 00:57:59,889
Scott: Like it is gone, gone the end.

896
00:58:00,753 --> 00:58:02,600
Scott: And that's not cool, right?

897
00:58:03,261 --> 00:58:17,940
Scott: I'm a person who believes that is, you know, if humans are going to survive, right, it's like, what's the point of surviving if we cannot preserve our, you know, a very important note about what you said, though, MMOs did not let players run their own servers ever.

898
00:58:18,921 --> 00:58:19,081
Scott: Nope.

899
00:58:19,582 --> 00:58:21,426
Rym: And in fact, the people who did, they were charging money.

900
